The paper deals with detecting adversarial examples in deep neural networks, which is a topic that falls under the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision (cs.CV), and cryptography and security (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper proposes a new strategy called "feature squeezing" which involves manipulating the input features of the neural network, which could also fall under the sub-categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE). Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG, cs.CV, and cs.CR, followed by cs.AI and cs.NE.
